#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:8
msgid "Scene Settings and Project Default Settings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:9
msgid ""
"When you start working on a scene, automatically it will belong to the "
"current project, inheriting its settings and default folders. In this way"
" all the scenes belonging to a project are created with the same "
"settings, assuring the consistency of the production (see  :ref:`Managing"
" Projects <managing_projects>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:11
msgid ""
"Settings concern different tasks you may perform in Toonz, such as the "
"scanning, or cleanup process, the camera size and resolution, the frame "
"rate, the output options, etc. They can be accessed in dialogs you can "
"open with commands available in the related menu; for example the scan "
"and cleanup settings commands are available in the Scan & Cleanup menu."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:13
msgid ""
"Settings for a particular scene can always be changed independently from "
"the other ones, and will be automatically saved when the scene is saved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:15
msgid ""
"If you want to change the default values you can save current scene "
"settings as default, so that all new scenes created for that project will"
" have those values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:17
msgid "**To save current scene settings as project default settings:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:19
msgid ""
"Select File > Save Default Settings: all the settings from the current "
"scene will become the project default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:24
msgid "Choosing the Working Unit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:25
msgid ""
"Positions, distances and sizes can be expressed in several units of "
"measure: inches, millimeters, centimeters, fields and pixels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:27
msgid ""
"The field unit is equal to 1/2 inch on the horizontal, and it depends on "
"the A/R set in the field guide information of the Scene settings dialog "
"on the vertical (see  :ref:`Using the Work Area <using_the_work_area>`  "
"). For example if the A/R value is 1.38, two horizontal fields are equal "
"to an inch, while the vertical field is an inch divided by 1.38."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:29
msgid ""
"In the Files > Preferences > Interface dialog you can set the following "
"default unit:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:31
msgid ""
"The default Unit used to display all measures in text fields, and applied"
" when moving or changing the size of stage objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:33
msgid ""
"The default Camera Unit used to display and define the camera size in the"
" Xsheet > Camera Settings dialog (see  :ref:`Defining Camera Settings "
"<defining_camera_settings>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:35
msgid ""
"You can also express measures in an unit different from the default one "
"by entering after the value any of the following units and abbreviations:"
" in, inch,“, ‘ ‘ (double apostrophe), cm, mm, fld, field and px. As soon "
"as the value is entered it is converted in the default unit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:37
msgid ""
"If a value without a specific unit is used, it is supposed to be "
"expressed in the default unit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:39
msgid "**To set the default working units:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:41
msgid "Choose File > Preferences > Interface."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:43
msgid "Do one of the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:45
msgid "In the Unit option menu choose the unit you want to use as default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:47
msgid ""
"In the Camera Unit option menu choose the unit you want to use to express"
" the camera size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:52
msgid "Setting the Frame Rate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:53
msgid ""
"The frame rate is the number of frames per second of animation, and has "
"to be set according to the type of output you have to render, for "
"instance it has to be 25 for PAL output, or 30 for NTSC."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:55
msgid ""
"The current scene frame rate can be set in the Scene Settings dialog, and"
" it is displayed in the bottom bar of any viewer pane. In case the play "
"back is activated, the actual frame rate is displayed on its left."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:57
msgid ""
"Apart from affecting the playback speed when previewing or rendering a "
"scene, the frame rate also determines the frame count of an audio file "
"when it is imported into the xsheet (see  :ref:`Creating a Soundtrack "
"<creating_a_soundtrack>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:59
msgid ""
"Even if a scene has been composited with a specific frame rate for a "
"certain output, it is possible to render it out at a different frame rate"
" by using the Stretch option in Output Settings (see  :ref:`Choosing the "
"Output Settings <choosing_the_output_settings>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:61
msgid "**To set the frame rate:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:63
msgid "Choose Xsheet > Scene Settings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:65
msgid "In the Frame Rate text field set the frame rate value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:70
msgid "Defining Camera Settings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:71
msgid ""
"The Camera Settings dialog, that can be opened from the Xsheet menu, "
"contains parameters for defining the current camera size and resolution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:73
msgid ""
"More than one camera can be defined for each scene, in order to have "
"different output resolutions, or to shot only a particular area of the "
"scene (see  :ref:`Using the Stage Schematic <using_the_stage_schematic>`"
"  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:75
msgid ""
"The camera size can be expressed in any unit, but will be visualized in "
"the default one chosen in the Preferences > Interface dialog (see  "
":ref:`Choosing the Working Unit <choosing_the_working_unit>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:77
msgid "In Toonz the Camera is defined by different parameters:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:82
msgid "Width and Height, are the size of the camera usually expressed in inches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:84
msgid "AR is the aspect ratio value resulting by the Width/Height formula."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:86
msgid ""
"XPx and YPx that are the number of pixels for the Width and the Height "
"respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:88
msgid ""
"XDpi and YDpi that are the X and Y resolutions calculated using the "
"standard formulas: XDpi=XPx/Width, and, YDpi=YPx/Height. This two fields "
"can be forced having the same valu using the appropriate checkbox."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:90
msgid ""
"When inserting a value in one field, the others change accordingly as "
"needed for having a consistent camera. You can decide which set of value "
"has to be considered fixed by Toonz . The buttons of the top row and "
"leftmost column of the camera parameters let you selct which colum and "
"row of values has to be preserved by Toonz while changing the others as "
"needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:92
msgid ""
"The Use Current Level Settings button let you set the camera for framing "
"exactly the content of the selected level. Just press this button and "
"Toonz will calculate the appropriate values for the camera."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:94
msgid ""
"Camera resolutions can also be selected from a list of predefined "
"cameras. You can add any camera you define to the list, as well as remove"
" any predefined camera from the list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:96
msgid ""
"The predefined cameras list is saved in the file ``reslist.txt``  stored "
"in the projectroot (see  :ref:`Setting the Projectroot "
"<setting_the_projectroot>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:98
msgid "**To add a predefined camera resolution:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:100
msgid "Set the resolution and A/R for the camera you want to save."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:102
msgid "Click the + button on the right of the predefined cameras list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:104
msgid "Assign a name to the camera resolution and click the OK button."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:106
msgid "**To remove a predefined camera resolution:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:108
msgid ""
"Select the camera resolution you want to remove in the predefined cameras"
" list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:110
msgid "Click the - button on the right of the predefined cameras list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:115
msgid "Assigning Memory for the Undo Operations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:116
msgid ""
"All the operations performed in the software can be undone by using the "
"Edit > Undo command, even to go back for several steps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:118
msgid ""
"Undo operations require computer memory in order to be performed, and "
"some of them may require more memory than some others, according to their"
" complexity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:120
msgid ""
"To prevent most of the computer memory to be used by undo operations "
"while you work, a situation that slows down the software performance, it "
"is possible to set a limit for it by specifying the Undo Memory Size in "
"MB in the Files > Preferences > General dialog."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:122
msgid ""
"As soon as the limit is reached, the oldest undo operations will be "
"discarded to make room for the new ones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:127
msgid "Optimizing the Memory Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:128
msgid ""
"When working with raster images, predominantly being animation levels "
"scanned with Toonz, an extensive usage of computer memory may be required"
" during the cleanup, painting and rendering processes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:130
msgid ""
"After a certain amount of time the computer performance may worsen, as "
"the memory gets fragmented because of the several writing and reading "
"accesses. To prevent this behavior, the Minimize Raster Image "
"Fragmentation option can be activated in the Files > Preferences > "
"General dialog. When activated, a section of computer memory is reserved "
"and used only for operation concerning raster images."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:132
msgid ""
"If you are working mainly with vector images, that have been drawn inside"
" Toonz, this option should be deactivated, as the reserved memory section"
" would be unused by the computer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:134
msgid "The value set for this option is valid only after Toonz is restarted."
msgstr ""

